1
00:01:15,920 --> 00:01:18,840
The man who said,
"I'd rather be lucky than good,"

2
00:01:18,920 --> 00:01:21,120
saw deeply into life.

3
00:01:21,320 --> 00:01:25,120
People are afraid to face how great
a part of life is dependent on luck.

4
00:01:25,960 --> 00:01:29,200
It's scary to think so much
is out of one's control.

5
00:01:30,040 --> 00:01:34,000
There are moments in a match
when the ball hits the top of the net,

6
00:01:34,280 --> 00:01:38,840
and for a split second
it can either go forward or fall back.

7
00:01:39,800 --> 00:01:43,760
With a little luck,
it goes forward and you win.

8
00:01:43,800 --> 00:01:47,240
Or maybe it doesn't, and you lose.

9
00:01:51,520 --> 00:01:53,120
Sorry.

10
00:01:58,200 --> 00:02:00,120
Mr. Townsend.

11
00:02:05,280 --> 00:02:07,240
Just this way.

12
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:10,480
So the Beach Club Marbella,
tennis instructor.

13
00:02:10,560 --> 00:02:14,080
Stanford House.
Forte Village, Sardinia. Nice.

14
00:02:14,120 --> 00:02:16,120
Yes. I've had
a good deal of experience.

15
00:02:16,200 --> 00:02:17,720
Yeah, so I see.

16
00:02:17,800 --> 00:02:20,880
Now, I've heard very good things.
You don't miss playing professionally?

17
00:02:20,960 --> 00:02:22,680
I thank God every day
I don't have to do it.

18
00:02:22,760 --> 00:02:26,080
I hate the whole tennis tour thing.

19
00:02:26,160 --> 00:02:30,480
Constant traveling, and I was
never going to be Rusedski or Agassi.

20
00:02:30,560 --> 00:02:32,360
You have to really want it.

21
00:02:32,440 --> 00:02:34,320
Not that I have their talent.

22
00:02:34,800 --> 00:02:37,480
Well, your credentials
and references are excellent.

23
00:02:37,560 --> 00:02:39,400
And you want to live in London?

24
00:02:39,480 --> 00:02:42,520
Very much. Very much.

25
00:02:42,600 --> 00:02:45,840
We have a very
exclusive membership here.

26
00:02:45,920 --> 00:02:47,760
You can begin this weekend?

27
00:02:48,640 --> 00:02:51,240
Thank you. Thank you very much.

28
00:02:52,480 --> 00:02:55,360
That's your sofa,
which also doubles up as a bed.

29
00:02:55,440 --> 00:02:58,240
Which is great, you know,
'cause you can be watching some telly,

30
00:02:58,320 --> 00:03:00,360
ain't got the hassle
of having to go to a bedroom.

31
00:03:00,440 --> 00:03:02,800
You can just open it up, get your kip.

32
00:03:02,880 --> 00:03:05,040
Kitchen just through there.

33
00:03:05,120 --> 00:03:08,520
All your amenities, fixtures,
fittings, washer-dryer...

34
00:03:08,600 --> 00:03:09,840
All that stuff.

35
00:03:09,920 --> 00:03:12,400
Lovely view, not overlooked.

36
00:03:12,480 --> 00:03:14,400
So it's all good.

37
00:03:14,480 --> 00:03:17,000
This is 225 a week?

38
00:03:17,080 --> 00:03:20,760
Well, it's London, mate. Bang, mate.
If you don't like it, move to Leeds.

39
00:03:20,840 --> 00:03:22,640
D'you know what I mean?
You got a wok?

40
00:03:22,720 --> 00:03:25,520
You got a wok? It's one of those
Oriental, sort of conical pans.

41
00:03:25,560 --> 00:03:27,720
- No, no, no.
- The geezer who was in here before,

42
00:03:27,800 --> 00:03:30,800
he left one in there. You're
welcome to it. I'll throw that in.

43
00:03:30,880 --> 00:03:33,640
- I'll take it.
- That's a good choice.

44
00:03:48,680 --> 00:03:50,200
Very good.

45
00:04:02,880 --> 00:04:04,360
Chris Wilton.

46
00:04:04,400 --> 00:04:06,200
This is Tom Hewett.

47
00:04:06,280 --> 00:04:08,200
- Very nice to meet you. How do you do?
- Morning. Pleasure.

48
00:04:08,280 --> 00:04:10,000
I think Chris would be
the perfect instructor for you,

49
00:04:10,080 --> 00:04:12,800
and he's very patient.
Great at analyzing a player's faults.

50
00:04:12,840 --> 00:04:16,040
I'm so out of practice. I mean,
I haven't played since university,

51
00:04:16,120 --> 00:04:19,400
and I loved it, but I haven't
picked up a racket in bloody ages, so...

52
00:04:19,480 --> 00:04:21,000
Don't worry, it comes back.

53
00:04:21,080 --> 00:04:23,680
What you can't do is rush in,
be discouraged.

54
00:04:23,760 --> 00:04:25,080
OK.

55
00:04:25,120 --> 00:04:27,200
- Well, good luck.
- Thank you very much.

56
00:04:27,280 --> 00:04:29,360
- Over here.
- Brilliant.

57
00:04:41,200 --> 00:04:45,160
OK, so who was better, or tougher?
Henman or Agassi?

58
00:04:45,240 --> 00:04:47,520
- They were both great.
- Yeah, I know, but I mean,

59
00:04:47,600 --> 00:04:49,440
you held your own more than admirably.

60
00:04:49,520 --> 00:04:50,920
For a while.

61
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:53,520
But as the game goes on,
you see how really good they are.

62
00:04:53,600 --> 00:04:55,360
- Actually, I'll get this.
- No, no, no, no.

63
00:04:55,440 --> 00:04:57,920
- No, please, Tom, I insist. I insist.
- No, no, no, no, no.

64
00:04:58,000 --> 00:04:59,880
Get your dirty great forehand off.

65
00:05:01,320 --> 00:05:03,280
Thank you. I'll get the next one.

66
00:05:04,200 --> 00:05:06,160
So, do you need a lift after this?

67
00:05:06,200 --> 00:05:09,800
Actually, I'm looking for a music store.
I want to buy some CDs.

68
00:05:09,880 --> 00:05:13,560
Music around here?
I think there's one on the Fulham Road.

69
00:05:13,640 --> 00:05:15,760
And they'll have a decent opera section?

70
00:05:15,840 --> 00:05:17,880
Opera? You like opera, really?

71
00:05:17,960 --> 00:05:19,200
I love opera.

72
00:05:19,240 --> 00:05:22,400
Papa gives loads
to the Royal in Covent Garden.

73
00:05:22,480 --> 00:05:24,360
I know this is gonna sound a bit weird,

74
00:05:24,440 --> 00:05:26,760
but would you like to go
to the opera tomorrow night?

75
00:05:28,080 --> 00:05:29,840
To the opera?

76
00:05:29,920 --> 00:05:32,360
Yeah. We've got a box
and someone's not coming.

77
00:05:32,440 --> 00:05:34,920
It's La bloody Traviata.

78
00:05:34,960 --> 00:05:38,040
My God. I'd love to.

79
00:05:38,120 --> 00:05:40,960
Are you sure it's not an imposition?
Can I at least pay for my seat?

80
00:05:41,040 --> 00:05:43,640
It's not an imposition,
it'd be an absolute pleasure.

81
00:05:43,720 --> 00:05:47,880
I just like the fact that we both
share a love for opera. Brilliant.

82
00:05:50,000 --> 00:05:50,960
So?

83
00:05:51,040 --> 00:05:54,040
- I said to David and Melissa...
- Evening all. Hello, Mum.

84
00:05:54,120 --> 00:05:56,200
Hello, sweetie. Very nice to see you.

85
00:05:56,280 --> 00:05:59,080
- This is Chris. This is my father Alec.
- Hello. Good to meet you.

86
00:05:59,160 --> 00:06:01,080
I hear you're an
incredible tennis player.

87
00:06:01,160 --> 00:06:03,920
I played once, and then I gave up,
then I went back, then I gave up,

88
00:06:04,000 --> 00:06:05,200
- then I went back
- Rubbish.

89
00:06:05,280 --> 00:06:07,920
- I'm sure Tom exaggerated my game.
- I just got bored.

90
00:06:08,000 --> 00:06:10,040
- Good evening. My pleasure.
- Nice to meet you.

91
00:06:10,120 --> 00:06:12,680
- This is my sister... Chloe.
- There's a chair somewhere.

92
00:06:12,760 --> 00:06:14,800
- I'm Chloe. Nice to meet you.
- There's two more.

93
00:07:05,280 --> 00:07:09,200
Yeah, well, the olds say thank you
very much for the lovely flowers.

94
00:07:09,280 --> 00:07:12,400
They said it was very thoughtful,
and totally unnecessary.

95
00:07:12,480 --> 00:07:16,840
But off the record, well done, A plus,
'cause they love that sort of thing.

96
00:07:16,920 --> 00:07:20,480
Oh, they're lovely people.
And your sister's very bright.

97
00:07:20,560 --> 00:07:23,200
Frighteningly so at times. But...

98
00:07:23,280 --> 00:07:26,280
Anyway, she thought you were terrific,
and she wanted to invite you

99
00:07:26,360 --> 00:07:29,240
to our country house
with the parents on Sunday.

100
00:07:29,320 --> 00:07:32,280
'Cause they're having a party,
there'll be some good people.

101
00:07:32,360 --> 00:07:36,680
And I'll play you some great music,
because Dad's got an epic collection.

102
00:07:55,040 --> 00:07:56,920
Chlo-Chlo, do you wanna have
a knock with Chris for a bit?

103
00:07:57,000 --> 00:07:58,840
It's just that
it's 5:00 somewhere, darling,

104
00:07:58,920 --> 00:08:01,080
and I've some serious
cocktails to start making.

105
00:08:01,160 --> 00:08:04,160
Irish! Have you ever had a
Cuba libre or a caipirinha?

106
00:08:04,240 --> 00:08:06,680
Lt'd be really boring
for Chris to play with me on my own.

107
00:08:06,760 --> 00:08:09,480
It's really boring for him
to play with me, but he's a good sport.

108
00:08:09,560 --> 00:08:12,360
And anyway, you've got better
legs than I've got. Chop-chop.

109
00:08:12,440 --> 00:08:15,400
Don't be silly. I teach people
who have never held a racket before.

110
00:08:15,480 --> 00:08:18,320
- I'm so bad.
- That's how you get better.

111
00:08:18,400 --> 00:08:20,240
Playing with a stronger player. Come on.

112
00:08:20,320 --> 00:08:22,040
OK.

113
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:43,280
Was I dreadful?

114
00:08:43,360 --> 00:08:46,120
Not at all.
You have a very unique style.

115
00:08:46,200 --> 00:08:50,080
Yeah, it's called clumsy.
How did you get to be so good anyway?

116
00:08:50,160 --> 00:08:52,480
Tom says you played
with some of the real greats.

117
00:08:52,560 --> 00:08:55,440
For me, it was a way out
of a poor existence.

118
00:08:55,520 --> 00:08:58,480
Caught the eye of a good coach.
I don't know.

119
00:08:59,600 --> 00:09:01,600
It all came so easy at first.

120
00:09:01,960 --> 00:09:04,240
- Do you enjoy teaching?
- Not really.

121
00:09:04,720 --> 00:09:06,240
I mean, it's OK for now,

122
00:09:06,320 --> 00:09:09,040
but I'd cut my throat
if I thought I had to do it forever.

123
00:09:09,120 --> 00:09:10,960
I'd like to do something with my life.

124
00:09:11,040 --> 00:09:14,600
You know, special.
I'd like to make a contribution.

125
00:09:14,680 --> 00:09:17,920
So, you're a poor boy
from Ireland come to London.

126
00:09:18,280 --> 00:09:19,720
I love it.

127
00:09:19,800 --> 00:09:22,200
It's so exciting and alive.

128
00:09:22,280 --> 00:09:24,600
I've never seen so much art or theater.

129
00:09:24,680 --> 00:09:26,880
Not that I've taken
much advantage of it yet.

130
00:09:26,920 --> 00:09:29,600
Well, look, if you'd like someone
to show you around,

131
00:09:29,680 --> 00:09:33,400
I grew up in Belgravia. I'd be happy
to take you to all the good places.

132
00:09:33,480 --> 00:09:34,720
That'd be great.

133
00:09:35,000 --> 00:09:38,760
On one condition: I buy the tickets.

134
00:09:38,800 --> 00:09:40,560
Oh, dear, is that going to be an issue?

135
00:09:40,640 --> 00:09:43,400
I'm afraid it is.
I'm very old-fashioned.

136
00:09:43,440 --> 00:09:46,160
But actually,
I did read something about the...

137
00:09:46,240 --> 00:09:48,520
...exhibition in the Saatchi Gallery.

138
00:09:48,600 --> 00:09:52,480
That's perfect.
It'd be my pleasure to take you.

139
00:09:52,520 --> 00:09:54,720
You're very kind to offer this.

140
00:09:54,800 --> 00:09:57,200
Can I at least give you
some free tennis lessons?

141
00:09:57,280 --> 00:09:58,960
OK, it's a deal.

142
00:09:59,040 --> 00:10:01,440
How about Wednesday for the Saatchi?

143
00:10:01,520 --> 00:10:03,000
I can do that.

144
00:10:03,080 --> 00:10:06,520
- Shall we meet for lunch first?
- It's a date.

145
00:10:06,600 --> 00:10:09,360
I'd better get ready.
Your guests will be arriving soon.

146
00:10:09,400 --> 00:10:11,320
Yeah, yeah. Of course. Go.

147
00:10:11,400 --> 00:10:14,560
A sweaty tennis player's
hardly what they expect.

148
00:11:11,000 --> 00:11:14,360
So who's my next victim?

149
00:11:15,560 --> 00:11:16,680
You?

150
00:11:17,280 --> 00:11:19,280
I haven't played table tennis
in quite a while.

151
00:11:20,120 --> 00:11:22,840
Would you like to play
for a thousand pounds a game?

152
00:11:24,640 --> 00:11:26,280
What did I walk into?

153
00:11:37,320 --> 00:11:39,640
What did I walk into?

154
00:11:40,960 --> 00:11:42,960
It's like this.

155
00:11:43,720 --> 00:11:45,760
- May I?
- Please.

156
00:11:47,560 --> 00:11:52,000
You have to lean in,
and hit through the ball.

157
00:11:54,960 --> 00:11:57,840
I was doing just fine
until you showed up.

158
00:11:57,920 --> 00:12:00,080
The story of my life.

159
00:12:00,160 --> 00:12:01,600
So, tell me,

160
00:12:01,640 --> 00:12:04,440
what's a beautiful, young,
American Ping-Pong player doing

161
00:12:04,520 --> 00:12:06,760
mingling amongst
the British upper class?

162
00:12:11,560 --> 00:12:15,920
Did anyone ever tell you,
you play a very aggressive game?

163
00:12:18,560 --> 00:12:21,480
Did anyone ever tell you
you've very sensual lips?

164
00:12:25,680 --> 00:12:28,880
- Extremely aggressive.
- I'm naturally competitive.

165
00:12:29,960 --> 00:12:31,960
Is it off-putting?

166
00:12:33,880 --> 00:12:36,400
I'll have to think
about that for a while.

167
00:12:39,880 --> 00:12:40,960
There you are.

168
00:12:41,040 --> 00:12:43,080
I wanted to introduce you
to Chris Wilton.

169
00:12:43,160 --> 00:12:46,200
Chris Wilton,
this is Nola Rice, my fiancée.

170
00:12:48,080 --> 00:12:50,480
So, you're the tennis pro.

171
00:12:50,560 --> 00:12:52,520
- Hello, darling.
- My pleasure.

172
00:12:52,600 --> 00:12:54,960
He was trying to have
his way with me over the table.

173
00:12:55,000 --> 00:12:57,800
Oh, really? Yeah, well,
you'd better watch out for this one.

174
00:12:57,880 --> 00:12:59,920
He's made a living out of hustling.

175
00:13:00,280 --> 00:13:03,000
I'll be ready for you next time.

176
00:13:04,840 --> 00:13:08,400
- I'll see you outside.
- Oh, yeah.

177
00:13:15,200 --> 00:13:17,480
She's quite something, isn't she?

178
00:13:19,600 --> 00:13:22,680
- How long have you been together?
- Six months.

179
00:13:22,760 --> 00:13:24,880
Jesus, yeah, six months!

180
00:13:24,960 --> 00:13:27,360
She came over to study acting,
and I met her at a party

181
00:13:27,440 --> 00:13:29,520
that I'd crashed
and she'd crashed, and...

182
00:13:29,600 --> 00:13:32,280
...one thing led to another.

183
00:13:33,040 --> 00:13:36,040
Obviously, it's taken Mother quite
a long time to get used to the idea

184
00:13:36,120 --> 00:13:37,640
that I'm serious about her, but...

185
00:13:37,720 --> 00:13:38,720
To be honest with you,

186
00:13:38,800 --> 00:13:41,080
Mother's always had
this funny little agenda for me

187
00:13:41,160 --> 00:13:44,440
which doesn't really involve
marrying a struggling actress.

188
00:13:44,480 --> 00:13:46,600
Especially an American one.

189
00:13:48,200 --> 00:13:50,560
But I am crazy about her.

190
00:13:50,640 --> 00:13:54,320
Anyway, I think we should all go to
dinner next week. What do you think?

191
00:13:54,520 --> 00:13:56,400
- I'd love to.
- Excellent.

192
00:13:56,480 --> 00:14:00,000
Now, Irish, how about a little drop
of Scottish before supper?

193
00:14:00,080 --> 00:14:03,400
- Why not.
- Lead on. Quickly.

194
00:14:43,240 --> 00:14:45,880
These afternoons have been great.

195
00:14:46,640 --> 00:14:49,880
I'm so glad your schedule
allows you so much time off.

196
00:14:49,960 --> 00:14:51,560
Yes, it's fun.

197
00:14:51,640 --> 00:14:54,280
Although it wouldn't hurt
to have a few more pupils.

198
00:14:56,520 --> 00:14:58,520
Do you need money?

199
00:14:58,600 --> 00:15:00,400
God, no.

200
00:15:00,680 --> 00:15:02,280
No, I'm fine.

201
00:15:02,320 --> 00:15:05,040
It's very sweet of you to ask,
but I don't.

202
00:15:11,200 --> 00:15:14,720
I'm only asking
because I care about you.

203
00:15:32,440 --> 00:15:35,280
Shall we go to your place or mine?

204
00:15:35,320 --> 00:15:37,600
I don't think mine's
quite what you're used to.

205
00:15:37,680 --> 00:15:41,560
Shut up. I think yours'll be just great.

206
00:16:01,360 --> 00:16:04,880
You've been seeing a lot
of Chris Wilton lately, I understand.

207
00:16:04,960 --> 00:16:08,560
- Yeah. He's very nice.
- I liked him.

208
00:16:08,640 --> 00:16:11,400
I just don't understand
what he's aiming for.

209
00:16:11,480 --> 00:16:14,360
He certainly doesn't want to be
a tennis pro for the rest of his life.

210
00:16:14,400 --> 00:16:16,680
Well, I find him very likeable.

211
00:16:16,760 --> 00:16:20,200
He's fought his way up the only way
open to him, and he's not trivial.

212
00:16:20,280 --> 00:16:24,560
I had a very interesting conversation
the other day about Dostoyevsky.

213
00:16:24,640 --> 00:16:26,600
Can't we do something for him?

214
00:16:26,680 --> 00:16:29,000
A place in one of
your companies or something?

215
00:16:29,040 --> 00:16:30,360
Has he expressed a desire?

216
00:16:30,440 --> 00:16:34,080
No, but... he's open,
you know, about his future.

217
00:16:34,160 --> 00:16:36,400
He really wants
to make something of his life.

218
00:16:36,480 --> 00:16:38,520
Chloe, be careful.

219
00:16:38,600 --> 00:16:42,520
Tom's involved with a woman I have
reservations about. Don't rush off.

220
00:16:42,600 --> 00:16:45,520
Tom's happy with Nola.
You're prejudiced 'cause she's American.

221
00:16:45,560 --> 00:16:47,440
She's spoilt and temperamental.

222
00:16:47,520 --> 00:16:49,360
She's an actress, they're emotional.

223
00:16:49,440 --> 00:16:52,680
She's deluding herself, and she's moody.
She's not right for Tom.

224
00:16:52,760 --> 00:16:56,000
Well, I care very deeply for Chris,
and I think he feels the same way.

225
00:16:56,040 --> 00:16:58,400
- Who are you talking about?
- Nola.

226
00:17:11,200 --> 00:17:13,520
- Have you been waiting ages?
- Hello. Not at all.

227
00:17:13,600 --> 00:17:16,080
Traffic was awful.
The others'll be here in a minute.

228
00:17:16,160 --> 00:17:18,040
They're probably
stuck in it somewhere.

229
00:17:18,120 --> 00:17:20,040
Can I have a champagne cocktail, please?

230
00:17:22,240 --> 00:17:26,320
One of your father's associates spoke to
me today about the possibility of a job.

231
00:17:26,400 --> 00:17:27,960
Did you say anything?

232
00:17:28,040 --> 00:17:32,440
Look, I just told Papa to keep his
eyes open if anything juicy opened up,

233
00:17:32,480 --> 00:17:35,320
so you could have first option,
if you wanted it.

234
00:17:35,840 --> 00:17:38,080
- You're not cross, are you?
- God, no.

235
00:17:38,160 --> 00:17:41,040
It's extremely thoughtful of you.

236
00:17:42,600 --> 00:17:44,600
Thanks.

237
00:17:44,680 --> 00:17:46,640
What do you think?

238
00:17:47,720 --> 00:17:49,720
