to leave your wife and marry Miss Rice?

1676
01:50:20,520 --> 01:50:22,600
No, I did not.

1677
01:50:22,960 --> 01:50:25,320
I mean, it's possible
she had that fantasy.

1678
01:50:26,280 --> 01:50:29,560
And, obviously, she wrote that I did.

1679
01:50:35,000 --> 01:50:37,720
But I tried to finesse
that point with her.

1680
01:50:37,800 --> 01:50:40,040
I didn't want the
sexual relationship to end,

1681
01:50:40,120 --> 01:50:42,200
but I'm not gonna break up my home.

1682
01:50:43,920 --> 01:50:46,880
My wife and I are
trying very hard to have a baby.

1683
01:50:46,920 --> 01:50:50,600
We've seen several
fertility doctors, et cetera.

1684
01:50:51,680 --> 01:50:55,280
You can check that out if you like,
but I beg you to be discreet.

1685
01:50:55,360 --> 01:50:57,400
But you did lead her on,

1686
01:50:57,480 --> 01:51:00,280
so that she had the impression
you were unhappy at home.

1687
01:51:00,960 --> 01:51:03,240
I tried to tip-toe around it
and not lead her on,

1688
01:51:03,320 --> 01:51:06,080
but she's going to believe
what she wants to believe.

1689
01:51:06,960 --> 01:51:12,400
Look, don't irresponsibly run roughshod
over this and wreck people's lives.

1690
01:51:13,040 --> 01:51:15,880
I mean, there is no case
because I would not harm anyone,

1691
01:51:15,960 --> 01:51:18,040
much less Nola Rice.

1692
01:51:23,400 --> 01:51:26,320
Isn't it obvious
that somebody killed her neighbor,

1693
01:51:26,360 --> 01:51:28,400
and she walked in when it was happening?

1694
01:51:30,280 --> 01:51:33,800
God, I beg you, don't go on
a fishing expedition over this and...

1695
01:51:34,200 --> 01:51:36,200
...wreck people's lives.

1696
01:51:36,280 --> 01:51:39,360
My family, my marriage is at stake.

1697
01:51:40,440 --> 01:51:43,080
We just have to
check out everything in a murder case.

1698
01:51:43,160 --> 01:51:45,560
OK, but I'm not your man.

1699
01:51:46,040 --> 01:51:49,280
I know it's not the most
honorable thing to cheat on your wife,

1700
01:51:49,360 --> 01:51:51,600
but that does not make me a murderer.

1701
01:51:51,760 --> 01:51:54,680
We're... obligated
to review the situation.

1702
01:51:54,760 --> 01:51:56,760
I understand
it's sensitive stuff for you.

1703
01:51:56,840 --> 01:51:58,440
And if we have to talk to you again,

1704
01:51:58,520 --> 01:52:00,840
we'll do everything in our power
to keep it very private.

1705
01:52:00,920 --> 01:52:02,440
Your personal life's your own.

1706
01:52:02,520 --> 01:52:06,360
We're not making any moral judgments,
just investigating a crime.

1707
01:52:16,560 --> 01:52:18,640
I understand.

1708
01:52:19,560 --> 01:52:21,200
Look...

1709
01:52:21,280 --> 01:52:23,480
...if you have to get
in contact with me again,

1710
01:52:23,560 --> 01:52:25,560
which, God in heaven,
I hope you don't,

1711
01:52:25,640 --> 01:52:27,600
please call me on my mobile.

1712
01:52:28,040 --> 01:52:30,080
This is my number.

1713
01:52:31,960 --> 01:52:33,560
Thanks.

1714
01:52:34,280 --> 01:52:35,240
One other thing.

1715
01:52:35,320 --> 01:52:37,720
Do you own or have access to a shotgun?

1716
01:52:39,920 --> 01:52:41,360
Me?

1717
01:52:41,560 --> 01:52:42,760
No.

1718
01:52:42,840 --> 01:52:46,720
My father-in-law shoots
on the estate, but not me.

1719
01:52:46,800 --> 01:52:48,960
You can check it out, but...

1720
01:52:49,960 --> 01:52:53,920
...I beg you to consider mine
and his position.

1721
01:52:54,000 --> 01:52:56,080
Of course.

1722
01:52:59,080 --> 01:53:01,040
Thank you.

1723
01:53:09,680 --> 01:53:11,680
So, what do you think?

1724
01:53:12,200 --> 01:53:14,000
I think it's what it looks like.

1725
01:53:14,080 --> 01:53:16,120
Someone robbed and killed Mrs. Eastby,

1726
01:53:16,200 --> 01:53:19,760
who was surprised leaving,
and killed Nola Rice.

1727
01:53:20,800 --> 01:53:24,360
Yeah, I know. I know, it's got
drug robbery written all over it.

1728
01:53:24,440 --> 01:53:26,440
He's 'specting a baby.

1729
01:53:26,640 --> 01:53:29,040
OK, he's not gonna win
a medal for fidelity, but...

1730
01:53:30,200 --> 01:53:31,800
...we can find out discreetly enough

1731
01:53:31,880 --> 01:53:34,880
whether the Hewetts
had a shotgun unaccounted for.

1732
01:53:36,760 --> 01:53:40,840
I don't think that he would know the
first thing about stealing one though,

1733
01:53:40,920 --> 01:53:43,720
never mind sawing one off.

1734
01:53:44,560 --> 01:53:47,520
It's a bit of a stretch.
He's got no previous convictions.

1735
01:53:47,600 --> 01:53:49,320
Not even a speeding ticket.

1736
01:53:49,400 --> 01:53:52,200
The coroner says
that Eastby was killed first.

1737
01:53:52,280 --> 01:53:54,600
- Yeah.
- There's no sign of a forced entry.

1738
01:53:54,680 --> 01:53:56,920
So Mrs. Eastby knew the killer,
if she let him in.

1739
01:53:57,000 --> 01:53:58,480
Well, come on, Mike.

1740
01:53:58,560 --> 01:54:00,400
Ninety percent
of the crimes we go out on,

1741
01:54:00,440 --> 01:54:02,600
people open their doors
and invite the criminals in.

1742
01:54:02,680 --> 01:54:05,000
Yeah, I know, you're right.
I'm just thinking out loud.

1743
01:54:05,080 --> 01:54:08,040
- It's just he's got a real motive.
- Yeah, maybe.

1744
01:54:08,120 --> 01:54:12,720
But a motive, as you and I
both painfully know, is not a case.

1745
01:54:12,800 --> 01:54:15,840
I'm torn because the Rice murder
was clearly an afterthought,

1746
01:54:15,920 --> 01:54:17,760
but I'd love to pursue it a little more.

1747
01:54:17,840 --> 01:54:21,200
But I'm reluctant to fish around
and cause problems for everybody.

1748
01:54:21,280 --> 01:54:23,560
Well, if something develops,
we can pursue it.

1749
01:54:23,640 --> 01:54:26,360
I doubt anything's
gonna drop into our laps.

1750
01:56:24,120 --> 01:56:25,800
Chris.

1751
01:56:35,760 --> 01:56:37,520
Nola...

1752
01:56:39,600 --> 01:56:41,840
...it wasn't easy.

1753
01:56:42,800 --> 01:56:45,600
But when the time came,
I could pull the trigger.

1754
01:56:47,480 --> 01:56:50,480
You never know who your neighbors are
till there's a crisis.

1755
01:56:52,080 --> 01:56:56,280
You can learn to push the guilt
under the rug and... go on.

1756
01:56:57,480 --> 01:56:59,240
You have to.

1757
01:56:59,320 --> 01:57:01,840
Otherwise it overwhelms you.

1758
01:57:01,920 --> 01:57:04,080
And what about me?

1759
01:57:04,120 --> 01:57:06,880
What about the next-door neighbor?

1760
01:57:07,640 --> 01:57:10,640
I had no involvement
in this awful affair.

1761
01:57:12,080 --> 01:57:17,000
Is there no problem about me
having to die as an innocent bystander?

1762
01:57:18,920 --> 01:57:23,320
The innocent are sometimes slain
to make way for a grander scheme.

1763
01:57:25,400 --> 01:57:27,640
You were collateral damage.

1764
01:57:27,720 --> 01:57:30,200
So was your own child.

1765
01:57:34,440 --> 01:57:36,440
Sophocles said:

1766
01:57:37,920 --> 01:57:40,120
"To never have been born

1767
01:57:40,720 --> 01:57:43,200
may be the greatest boon of all."

1768
01:57:45,560 --> 01:57:47,880
Prepare to pay the price, Chris.

1769
01:57:48,800 --> 01:57:50,960
Your actions were clumsy.

1770
01:57:51,040 --> 01:57:52,720
Full of holes.

1771
01:57:52,800 --> 01:57:56,000
Almost like someone
begging to be found out.

1772
01:57:59,480 --> 01:58:02,480
It would be fitting
if I were apprehended

1773
01:58:02,520 --> 01:58:04,440
and punished.

1774
01:58:05,560 --> 01:58:09,280
At least there would be
some small sign ofjustice.

1775
01:58:09,360 --> 01:58:12,360
Some small...

1776
01:58:13,040 --> 01:58:16,480
...measure of hope
for the possibility of meaning.

1777
01:58:18,880 --> 01:58:22,040
Chris Wilton killed them.
I see how he did it.

1778
01:58:22,120 --> 01:58:23,880
What?

1779
01:58:25,080 --> 01:58:26,640
It's as we speculated

1780
01:58:26,720 --> 01:58:29,120
and said was too elaborate,
but that's what he did.

1781
01:58:29,200 --> 01:58:32,280
He killed the next-door neighbor first
to throw us off the scent

1782
01:58:32,360 --> 01:58:34,040
and set up the appearance of a robbery.

1783
01:58:34,120 --> 01:58:35,120
He waited in the hall.

1784
01:58:35,200 --> 01:58:37,080
He knew she'd be back
the same time as usual,

1785
01:58:37,160 --> 01:58:40,440
and he killed her, making it seem like
she surprised a burglar running out.

1786
01:58:40,520 --> 01:58:42,640
He planned it all so he could
make the theater in time

1787
01:58:42,720 --> 01:58:44,960
to strengthen his alibi,
if one became necessary.

1788
01:58:45,040 --> 01:58:47,560
Now, I haven't figured out
the weapon problem,

1789
01:58:47,640 --> 01:58:49,120
and I know it's a lot to ask a jury,

1790
01:58:49,160 --> 01:58:51,360
but the correctness of it
came to me in my sleep

1791
01:58:51,440 --> 01:58:53,200
and I am going to break this case.

1792
01:58:53,280 --> 01:58:55,120
I hate to be the bearer
of bad news, Mike.

1793
01:58:55,200 --> 01:58:56,160
What?

1794
01:58:56,240 --> 01:58:58,200
Not that your dream
isn't of primary interest to a jury.

1795
01:58:58,240 --> 01:58:59,520
What's the bad news?

1796
01:58:59,600 --> 01:59:02,480
There was another shooting
in the area last night, 4am.

1797
01:59:02,560 --> 01:59:05,280
A drug addict killed.
Looks like a drug sale turned nasty.

1798
01:59:05,360 --> 01:59:08,600
What, and he confessed
to killing two women before he died?

1799
01:59:08,680 --> 01:59:10,360
No, he didn't have to.

1800
01:59:10,440 --> 01:59:13,640
The old woman's wedding ring
was right in his pocket.

1801
01:59:14,320 --> 01:59:17,560
- No.
- Name and date engraved right on it.

1802
01:59:18,560 --> 01:59:21,760
- I don't believe it.
- I know. I know.

1803
01:59:21,840 --> 01:59:24,160
Your case looked good, lots of motive.

1804
01:59:24,200 --> 01:59:26,480
But his motive
was pretty strong too. Heroin.

1805
01:59:26,800 --> 01:59:29,200
Junkie with a long string
of convictions.

1806
01:59:29,800 --> 01:59:31,800
Killed by one of his own, no doubt.

1807
01:59:31,880 --> 01:59:33,720
Come on, I'll buy you breakfast.

1808
01:59:33,800 --> 01:59:36,120
You can traumatize me
with the rest of your dreams.

1809
01:59:36,200 --> 01:59:37,600
No, wait.

1810
01:59:37,640 --> 01:59:41,640
What if Wilton did it, threw the
jewels away, this guy finds them?

1811
01:59:43,080 --> 01:59:46,440
I don't know.
See what tonight's dream tells you.

1812
01:59:46,520 --> 01:59:49,240
I'm sure a jury will be interested.

1813
01:59:49,320 --> 01:59:51,160
Come on.

1814
01:59:52,520 --> 01:59:53,760
I give up.

1815
01:59:53,840 --> 01:59:55,640
I knew Wilton didn't do it.

1816
01:59:55,720 --> 01:59:58,040
He's another poor schmuck
who cheated on his wife.

1817
01:59:58,120 --> 02:00:01,440
When you see those pictures
of Nola Rice, you can see why though.

1818
02:00:02,160 --> 02:00:04,920
What a world. Am I right?

1819
02:00:05,400 --> 02:00:08,360
Careful, careful.
I'm always afraid they'll drop.

1820
02:00:08,440 --> 02:00:11,440
- Oh, chill out, Dad.
- Babies are so, so soft.

1821
02:00:11,520 --> 02:00:13,480
Right. Champagne.

1822
02:00:13,520 --> 02:00:15,760
- I think he's got your eyes, Chloe.
- Really?

1823
02:00:15,840 --> 02:00:18,200
I think he's got
your coloring darling, I really do.

1824
02:00:18,280 --> 02:00:21,520
Mummy, you can't tell anything yet.
They change all the time.

1825
02:00:22,880 --> 02:00:24,440
- My nephew.
- Uncle, Uncle Tom.

1826
02:00:24,520 --> 02:00:27,160
- Oh, look at these flowers.
- No, he does look like Christopher.

1827
02:00:27,240 --> 02:00:30,720
Actually, speaking of which, didn't you
move into Alan Sinclair's old office?

1828
02:00:30,800 --> 02:00:33,160
- You lucky swine.
- Oh, Mummy, look, he's dreaming.

1829
02:00:33,240 --> 02:00:34,720
Let's work on number two. Come on.

1830
02:00:34,800 --> 02:00:38,160
Come on, he is a handsome boy.
Look at that face.

1831
02:00:38,240 --> 02:00:39,480
Yeah, he's gorgeous.

1832
02:00:39,560 --> 02:00:41,600
Right, here we are. Eleanor. Please...

1833
02:00:41,680 --> 02:00:43,040
- Chloe...
- Good stuff, Papa.

1834
02:00:43,080 --> 02:00:44,600
- Thank you, darling. There you are.
- There we go.

1835
02:00:44,680 --> 02:00:46,840
- It's all right, you stay there.
- I'll pass them round, shall I?

1836
02:00:46,880 --> 02:00:47,880
Please do.

1837
02:00:47,960 --> 02:00:49,040
- What a good idea.
- Darling, have one.

1838
02:00:49,080 --> 02:00:51,320
- To Terence Elliot Wilton.
- Yes.

1839
02:00:51,400 --> 02:00:53,800
With parents like Chloe and Chris,

1840
02:00:53,880 --> 02:00:56,680
this child will be great
at anything he sets his mind to.

1841
02:00:56,720 --> 02:00:58,280
- Thank you, Mummy.
- He will. He...

1842
02:00:58,360 --> 02:01:00,280
Do you know what,
I don't care if he's great.

1843
02:01:00,360 --> 02:01:01,680
I just hope that he's lucky.

1844
02:01:01,760 --> 02:01:03,360
- Oh, lovely.
- What a lovely thought.

1845
02:01:03,440 --> 02:01:04,760
- He probably will be.
- Absolutely adorable.

1846
02:01:04,840 --> 02:01:06,680
- Mummy, are you sure I'm allowed this?
- Yes, yes.

1847
02:01:06,760 --> 02:01:09,600
- Yes, of course you are.
- You haven't had any for months.

1848
02:01:09,640 --> 02:01:11,040
I'd get it down you now, while you can.

1849
02:01:11,120 --> 02:01:12,400
Isn't he handsome?
My God, he's handsome.

1850
02:01:12,480 --> 02:01:14,640
Bet you any money
the next one's a girl.

1851
02:01:16,800 --> 02:01:18,200
What are you saying about him?

1852
02:01:18,280 --> 02:01:20,280
I was just saying he's got
the most adorable cheeks.

1853
02:01:20,360 --> 02:01:24,320
We were just saying how handsome he is.
Just so extraordinarily handsome.

1854
02:01:24,400 --> 02:01:25,680
I wonder what he's thinking.

1855
02:01:25,720 --> 02:01:27,000
Well, you know, they said
he was a thinker. The nurses.

1856
02:01:27,080 --> 02:01:28,720
- Deep thoughts. Deep thoughts.
- Here we are.

1857
02:01:28,800 --> 02:01:30,720
- To Terence.
- To Terence.

1858
02:01:30,800 --> 02:01:33,480
- To Terence.
- And all that sail on him.

